            <div type="commentary">
                <p><!--commented out pending revision-->
                    <!--frag. of cippus; dated by Orsi to later C5 on basis of letters, but the necrop is C4-3 BC, and downdated to early C4 by Sacco; Orsi does not give the material of the stone; it is a funerary epigram, lines 2-7 in hexameter, the first prob. not verse but the name of decesased: - - - -AKE- - - | Kall[on]os tod[e] | sem[a p]||eriphr[on]|os en[use] |met[er]. Sacco follows Orsi's publ. for the drawing and general details; no info. on the stone itself in either. Sacco notes Dubois IGDS no.170 for another C4 parallel, using Ionic dialect in Doric Syracuse, this time from Gela (a pyxis, not a stone). Necropolis is C4-3, and with Ionic, Orsi's date too high, so S thinks first few decades of C4. No indication of location - should be in the Museum. Manganaro reads insteead Akesia tou Kallikrateos tode kalon sema - - - - Eriphradeos he medousa meter epoiei--></p>
            </div>
